# Database Rules

**Note:** This rule provides specific guidance for MongoDB/Mongoose. It complements the architectural principles in `nestjs-architecture.mdc` (always applied). For detailed schema and model patterns, see `nestjs-architecture.mdc` section 10.

## MongoDB with Mongoose

1. **Use MongoDB with Mongoose for database operations**
2. **Schemas in `database/schemas/` directory** (see `nestjs-architecture.mdc` section 1)
3. **Use Mongoose decorators from @nestjs/mongoose** (see `nestjs-architecture.mdc` section 10)

## Schema Structure

```typescript
import { Prop, Schema, SchemaFactory } from '@nestjs/mongoose';
import { Document, Types } from 'mongoose';

export type RequestDocument = Request & Document;

export enum RequestStatus {
  PENDING = 'pending',
  ACTIVE = 'active',
  CLOSED = 'closed',
}

@Schema({ timestamps: true })
export class Request {
  _id: Types.ObjectId;

  @Prop({ required: true, trim: true, index: 'text' })
  title: string;

  @Prop({ required: true, index: 'text' })
  description: string;

  @Prop({ type: Types.ObjectId, ref: 'User', required: true, index: true })
  buyerId: Types.ObjectId;

  @Prop({
    type: String,
    enum: Object.values(RequestStatus),
    default: RequestStatus.PENDING,
    index: true,
  })
  status: RequestStatus;

  createdAt: Date;
  updatedAt: Date;
}

export const RequestSchema = SchemaFactory.createForClass(Request);

// Indexes
RequestSchema.index({ buyerId: 1 });
RequestSchema.index({ status: 1 });
RequestSchema.index({ createdAt: -1 });
RequestSchema.index({ title: 'text', description: 'text' });
```

## Schema Registration in Modules

Register schemas in modules using `MongooseModule.forFeature()`:

```typescript
import { Module } from '@nestjs/common';
import { MongooseModule } from '@nestjs/mongoose';
import { Request, RequestSchema } from '../../database/schemas/request.schema';

@Module({
  imports: [
    MongooseModule.forFeature([
      { name: Request.name, schema: RequestSchema },
    ]),
  ],
  // ...
})
export class RequestsModule {}
```

## Model Injection Pattern

- Use Mongoose models for database access
- Inject models using `@InjectModel(Schema.name)`
- Models are injected as `Model<SchemaDocument>`
- Always register schemas in the module before injecting

```typescript
@Injectable()
export class RequestsService {
  constructor(
    @InjectModel(Request.name) private requestModel: Model<RequestDocument>,
  ) {}
}
```

## Database Indexes

Create indexes in schema definition or after schema creation:
- `email` in users (unique)
- `buyerId`, `category`, `status`, `createdAt` in requests
- `requestId`, `sellerId`, `status` in proposals
- `senderId`, `receiverId` in messages
- Text index on `title`, `description` in requests for search

```typescript
// In schema definition
@Prop({ required: true, unique: true, index: true })
email: string;

// After schema creation
Schema.index({ field: 1 }); // ascending
Schema.index({ field: -1 }); // descending
Schema.index({ field1: 1, field2: -1 }); // compound
Schema.index({ title: 'text', description: 'text' }); // text search
```

## ObjectId Usage

- Use `Types.ObjectId` for references and IDs
- IDs can be stored as `Types.ObjectId` or converted to `string`
- Use `new Types.ObjectId(id)` to convert string to ObjectId

## Naming Conventions

- Collection names: Mongoose automatically pluralizes (User → users)
- Field names: camelCase (e.g., `buyerId`, `createdAt`)
- Schema class names: PascalCase (e.g., `Request`, `User`)
- Document types: `SchemaDocument` (e.g., `RequestDocument`)
